    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-01-24T13:50:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-01-24T13:50:00-05:00" n="643"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d643">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">690D.91/1–2252: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Pakistan</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d643fn1">This telegram was repeated to London and
                        Paris.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-01-24T13:50:00-05:00"
                            >January 24, 1952—1:50 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>688. <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> seriously questions accuracy <gloss
                        target="#t_PM1">PM</gloss>’s analysis USSR intervention (<gloss
                        target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 745 Jan 21) and assumes <gloss
                        target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> shares this belief. <pb facs="0130" n="1180"
                        xml:id="pg_1180"/>
                    <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> requests <gloss target="#t_Emb1"
                        >Emb</gloss>’s estimate importance <gloss target="#t_PM1">PM</gloss>’s
                    statement re reexamination <gloss target="#t_GOP1">GOP</gloss>-USSR relations.
                    When occasion arises <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> shld stress to <gloss
                        target="#t_PM1">PM</gloss> our belief USSR action most likely motivated by
                    desire block further progress when Kashmir solution appears to be in sight. Thus
                        <gloss target="#t_Sov1">Sov</gloss> tactic if successful cld only prove
                    harmful to <gloss target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss>. Re Vyshinski’s explanation to
                        <persName corresp="#p_KCSM1">Zafrulla</persName> (<gloss target="#t_Embtel1"
                        >Embtel</gloss> 751 Jan 22)<note n="2" xml:id="d643fn2">
                        <p>In telegram 751 from Karachi, Jan. 22, Ambassador <persName
                                corresp="#p_WAM1">Warren</persName> reported as follows:</p>
                        <p>“We learned yesterday from <gloss target="#t_FonSecy1">FonSecy</gloss>
                            Baig, and later from <gloss target="#t_PriMin1">PriMin</gloss> in
                            conversation with <gloss target="#t_Amb1">Amb</gloss>, that <persName
                                corresp="#p_KCSM1">Zafrulla</persName> has reported a conversation
                            in which he asked Vyshinski to explain significance of Malik’s speech on
                            Kashmir. Vyshinski replied it had no special significance, it was just
                            normal participation in <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> debate. He
                            said Malik’s <gloss target="#t_ref1">ref</gloss> to a consembly was not
                            to the existing body but to a really representative one yet to be
                            elected.</p>
                        <p>“Baig expressed personal opinion motive behind Malik speech was to ‘throw
                            a spanner in the works’. He did not think it was intended to help the
                            Indians.” (690D.91/1–2252)</p>
                    </note> you shld note Malik clearly referred to present consembly and not to any
                    consembly yet to be elected Vyshinski to contrary notwithstanding. In any event
                    we have long ago learned to discount word of USSR spokesmen.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> may observe further to <gloss
                        target="#t_PM1">PM</gloss> that for present at least any <gloss
                        target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> res very likely to be vetoed by USSR. If final
                        <persName corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName> effort leads to agreement all
                    pts fol another visit to subcontinent, USSR wld be in weak position veto
                    resultant res. You may finally reaffirm to <gloss target="#t_PM1">PM</gloss> our
                    single purpose in seeing Kashmir issue to early successful conclusion. <gloss
                        target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> suggests further reference US-<gloss
                        target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss> mil aid program this connection not
                    desirable.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> will be kept informed London talks with
                        <persName corresp="#p_KCSM1">Zafrulla</persName> re US–UK views on immed
                    future course action <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName> which <gloss target="#t_Dept1"
                        >Dept</gloss> hopes will result deferment res until after final effort by
                        <persName corresp="#p_GDF1">Graham</persName>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_ADG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
